item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: We are New York City Bridge Runners. We come from various walks of life, unified by our passion for the city and pushing our athletic, social, and creative boundaries. Since a handful of runners first organized under the Bridge Runners moniker in 2004, our collective has grown incrementally. From neighborhood entrepreneurs and 9-to-5ers to creative tastemakers and internationally recognized athletes, we are connected by the bridges like the Five Boroughs themselves. The key to our movement is awareness. Awareness of the moment in which we run. Awareness of one another as we challenge ourselves physically. And awareness of that which transpired before us in the places we explore. We are New York City Bridge Runners. Come Run With Us.

item.title: Mike Saes
item.dc:creator: henrylee
item.content:encoded:
Bridge Running Pioneer Mike Saes Is About To Change Your Pace

Words by Noah Rubin with Mike Saes
Photos by Chris Shonting
When people hear Mike Saes is running, their first question is, ‚ "Who is he running from?"‚ The proud native New Yorker was born on the Lower East Side and raised in the West Village. The importance of foot skills have never been lost on Saes, coming up in early 80s New York amidst the mythical grit that still attracts people to this, the Greatest City on Earth. Catching tags on trains and dancing in the streets, with a blaring radio on his shoulder and a change-filled Kangol in his outstretched fist, Saes participated in the movement. That era's essence, still of infinite import to today's creative minds, inspired Saes to start the Urban Experience Project in 2001. This cultural hub gave shine to the work of hundreds of artists. Painting, photography, film, poetry, music, and theater coexisted in the Project's fresh exhibition environment. Feeling it was time to bring balance to his mind, body, and soul, Saes took the city's best architecture and flipped it into his own athletic playground in 2004. What started with late night cross-bridge solo runs has grown into the Bridge Runners. The collection of individuals now part of the movement, from Grafitti greats, to olympic medalists, to musicians, to Tour De France champion Lance Armstrong, are testament to the power of his compellingly simple idea. With fellow bridge runners he completed his first marathon—a practice he intends to continue into his 70s. Since then, every year Saes joins a handful of runners in completing their first 26.2 by any means necessary. Maybe Diddy ran the city, but don't get it twisted, the Bridge Runners and Saes run this place. Can you talk a little bit about the birth of the Bridge Runners? I was at Peter Luger's having lunch and I couldn't catch a cab back to Manhattan. I ended up running across the Williamsburg Bridge. The same thing happened a week later, except my friend drove me to the Brooklyn Bridge and I ran across. It was a hill and you saw lots of New York and it was a cool thing to run. That summer I started getting people to run the bridges with me at midnight. It caught the ear of some cool people, we joined together, and now it's a movement. When you were coming up in the city how did you perceive the bridges? I rode across the Brooklyn and the Manhattan as a kid, but there was a danger aspect to crossing the Williamsburg. You'd get your bike robbed, that was known. I never looked at them as something to run, I just looked at them as a way to get to doing something different on the other side. What they represent is something more than the common. That's what Bridge Runners is‚Äîmore than your average runners club. Even though you came up in the city, do you think running the bridges has changed your outlook on New York as a whole? I'm an old fart so it hasn't changed me, but I like introducing it to other runners, especially new New Yorkers. I love finding new streets that no one walks down, little hidden spots and best kept secrets. Anything under the bridge, over the bridge, or around the bridge is kinda dope to me. What's the usual reaction you get when you tell people you run bridges? Most people don't believe me, especially when I tell them I run marathons, too. Treadmills to me are wack and running Central Park to me is like running on a gerbil wheel. Running bridges is something different. To train for a half marathon or a marathon or an ultrathon, bridges are the way to go. How important is good gear to getting you motivated for a run? It's hard being a cool runner because the running world doesn't make it easy for us. It's more than just our personalities, it's also the gear. I'm hoping to design our own stuff so we can look fresh. Right now you have to coordinate to look dope, but I shouldn't have to stress about whether I can wear this grey top with those black shorts. We want younger people to feel how we do about running‚Äî that's the whole point. There's gotta be a uniform that represents cool runners. What kind of impact do you think changing peoples' perception of running might have? To me running is meditation and not a chore but a joy, so we look forward to running. We run to see each other and hang out‚Äîwe run as a team. Whenever I see people running by the by the water I bug out cause they're by themselves. If there's three or even four people things happen that wouldn't have if you were by yourself. I think when the ill communication is popping there'll be people running in every neighborhood and every bridge and you'll always be able to run as a group‚Äîthat'll change the game. Bridge Runners is a true club of running non-runners that run shit. What is the Bridge Runners master plan? The seeds have been planted and now they need to vegetate. Handle New York cause its the center of the world and once it's solid here, we spread our message globally. There's bridges everywhere, someone's gotta run 'em. I want people to experience the cultures in their hoods that they wouldn't otherwise. Supporting the community by running through it, experiencing it, and teaching it to younger runners. It's not just a health movement, it's a health/history/culture movement. We are the grandads of future Bridge Runners that will take other kids running and go to restaurants we've been going to forever. Eventually there'll be pictures of us at spots all over the city. We are the first generation of Bridge Runners. It's just begun.
